11-03-2026
Great 👍 Let’s continue with the 4th SOLID principle using the same 9-point structure.
This principle was introduced by Robert C. Martin and is closely related to the problems we saw in LSP.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
________________________________________
1️⃣ Definition (Interview Ready)
Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do not use.
In simple words:
Instead of one large interface, create multiple smaller and specific interfaces.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Core Idea
Large interfaces cause problems because:
•	classes must implement unnecessary methods
•	code becomes hard to maintain
•	it often leads to LSP violations
Bad design:
Large Interface
       ↓
Classes forced to implement methods they don't need
Good design:
Small Specific Interfaces
       ↓
Classes implement only what they need
________________________________________
3️⃣ Real-World Analogy
Think about a universal remote control.
Imagine one remote with 100 buttons:
•	TV
•	AC
•	Music system
•	Projector
•	Lights
But if you only have a TV, most buttons are useless.
Better design:
•	TV remote
•	AC remote
•	Music remote
Each device gets only the controls it needs.
This is Interface Segregation Principle.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Bad Design Example (ISP Violation)
Suppose we create a Worker interface.
interface Worker {

    void work();
    void eat();
}


Now implementations:
class HumanWorker implements Worker {

    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Human working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Human eating");
    }
}


Now robot worker:
class RobotWorker implements Worker {

    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Robot working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}


Problem:
Robot does not eat, but the interface forces it.
This violates ISP.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Refactored Design (Correct Approach)
Split the interface.
Step 1 — Create small interfaces
interface Workable {
    void work();
}
interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}


________________________________________
Step 2 — Implement only required interfaces
Human worker:
class HumanWorker implements Workable, Eatable {

    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Human working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Human eating");
    }
}


Robot worker:
class RobotWorker implements Workable {

    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Robot working");
    }
}


________________________________________
Runnable Example
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Workable human = new HumanWorker();
        human.work();

        Workable robot = new RobotWorker();
        robot.work();
    }
}


Output
Human working
Robot working
Robot is not forced to implement eat().
System follows ISP.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Advantages in Enterprise Systems
1️⃣ Cleaner interfaces
Classes implement only what they need.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Reduced coupling
Components are less dependent on unrelated functionality.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Easier maintenance
Changes in one interface do not affect unrelated classes.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Better scalability
New implementations can be added easily.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Common Interview Traps
Trap 1
Thinking ISP means many tiny interfaces everywhere.
Not true.
Interfaces should be logical and cohesive.
________________________________________
Trap 2
Confusing ISP with Single Responsibility Principle.
Difference:
Principle	Focus
SRP	One responsibility per class
ISP	Small, specific interfaces
________________________________________
Trap 3
Ignoring ISP in large APIs.
Huge interfaces create maintenance problems.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Relation with Spring Architecture
Frameworks like **Spring Boot use many small interfaces.
Example from Spring Data:
CrudRepository
PagingAndSortingRepository
JpaRepository
Each interface adds specific functionality.
Developers can choose the level they need.
Example:
interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long>
Spring internally uses ISP to keep APIs modular.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Scenario-Based Interview Question
Interview Question
You are designing a Smart Device system.
Devices include:
•	Printer
•	Scanner
•	Fax machine
Initial interface:
interface Machine {

    void print();
    void scan();
    void fax();
}


Problem:
A simple printer must implement:
scan()
fax()
even if it doesn't support them.
________________________________________
Correct Design
Split the interfaces.
interface Printer {
    void print();
}
interface Scanner {
    void scan();
}
interface Fax {
    void fax();
}


Implement:
SimplePrinter → Printer
PhotoCopier → Printer + Scanner
MultiFunctionPrinter → Printer + Scanner + Fax
Now each device implements only the functionality it supports.
This follows Interface Segregation Principle.
________________________________________
Interview-Ready Answer
Interface Segregation Principle states that clients should not be forced to depend on methods they do not use. Instead of large interfaces, we should create smaller, more specific interfaces so that implementing classes only depend on the functionality they actually require.
________________________________________
✅ Only one SOLID principle remains:
Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP).
This one is extremely important in Spring applications because it directly explains Dependency Injection used in **Spring Boot.
If you want, next I will explain DIP, which usually appears in almost every Java backend interview.

